{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515943"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:36:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:36:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12526"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12526"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.22,0.28,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5027"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112948"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5027"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12526"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94980"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1446"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8346"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8359"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12190"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35583"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112948"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 79-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a 3-hour history of progressively worsening pain in the right forefoot with associated discolouration of the toes and mild reduction of motor function and sensation. This is his first episode of sharp pain which occurred while at rest and is worse on movement. His medical history includes hyperthyroidism and hypertension for which he takes carbimazole and perindopril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he has an irregularly irregular radial pulse at 140/min, and his blood pressure is 138/75mmHg. Other vitals are within normal limits. There are no signs of trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis right forefoot is cold and pale. Capillary refill time is delayed and there is reduced venous filling in the foot. The right femoral pulse is easily palpable. The right popliteal, dorsalis pedis and posterior tibial pulses are absent. The patient has slight reduced movement of the toes and forefoot with preserved ankle and knee movement. He also has mildly reduced sensation in the toes. Oxycodone is given to manage the pain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following options is the next most appropriate step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous heparin","Catheter-directed thrombolysis","Embolectomy","DC cardioversion","Metoprolol"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute limb ischaemia is a surgical emergency requiring prompt vascular input. \u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous heparin\u003C/strong\u003E should be commenced as soon as practical to prevent further local and systemic complications. Early vascular consultation should be sought to guide the conservative versus operative route of management. Further investigations should be carried out including routine bloods, venous blood gas for lactate, group and hold, ECG, Doppler ultrasound scan and potential CT angiography. Definitive treatment will depend on the viability of the limb, aetiology and location of the lesion. The Rutherford categories is useful for categorising the viability of the limb:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI = viable\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIIa = marginally threated\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIIb = immediately threatened\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIII = irreversible\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe full table can be found in references. In this scenario, the patient has Rutherford IIa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurgical intervention is warranted in Rutherford 2A/2B limbs,however urgency is dictated by the clinical presentation and trend of symptoms. If the cause was embolic, surgical options included embolectomy, intra-arterial thrombolysis and bypass surgery. If the cause was thrombotic, surgical options included angioplasty, intra-arterial thrombolysis and bypass surgery. These interventions, including \u003Cstrong\u003Ecatheter-directed thrombolysis\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eembolectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would only be considered after heparinisation had been started and imaging undertaken to define the site and extent of the obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThough this patient likely has atrial fibrillation as the cause of the embolus, this can be managed after the most pressing is addressed. It can be initially rate controlled with agents such as \u003Cstrong\u003Emetoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E and digoxin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The 6 \u0027P\u0027s of acute limb ischaemia are pain, pallor, poikilothermia, pulselessness, paresthesia, and paralysis."],"references":["Zemaitis MR, Boll JM, Dreyer MA. Peripheral Arterial Disease. [Updated 2022 Jul 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430745/","Brearley S. Acute leg ischaemia. BMJ. 2013 May 8;346:f2681. doi: 10.1136/bmj.f2681. PMID: 23657181.","Hardman RL, Jazaeri O, Yi J, Smith M, Gupta R. Overview of classification systems in peripheral artery disease. Semin Intervent Radiol. 2014 Dec;31(4):378-88. doi: 10.1055/s-0034-1393976. PMID: 25435665; PMCID: PMC4232437."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94980"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12526"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94980"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T16:28:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T16:28:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5027"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112948"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api